Process Data

rm(list = ls(all = TRUE)) 
#clear data

#install.packages(c("fpp2", "forecast", "TTR"), dependencies = TRUE, repos = "https://cloud.r-project.org")

data <- read.csv("~/Documents/Hmw493/data_week.csv")

Invoking time series functions to analyze rainfall effect

##### Representing Data as Time Series Objects #####
rainfall <- data[,13]

yy <- ts(rainfall, frequency = 52,start = c(2015,1)) # coverts sales data as time series object with start date and weekly frequency

plot.ts(yy)                                 # ALWAYS plot time series to see patterns: trend, cycle, variance over time

##### Time Series Decomposition  #####

## Rainfall: What's the rainfall rate? How do we obtain seasonally adjusted rainfall?
rainfall_d <- decompose(yy) 
rainfall.trend <- rainfall_d$trend
rainfall.seasonal <- rainfall_d$seasonal
rainfall.resid <- rainfall_d$random
rainfall.season.adj <- yy - rainfall.seasonal                                   # seasonally adjusted rainfall
plot.ts(cbind(yy,rainfall.trend, rainfall.seasonal, rainfall.resid, rainfall.season.adj))

##### Holt-Winters Filter  #####

###
#beta = beta parameter of Holt-Winters Filter. If set to False, the function will do exponential smoothing.
#gamma  = gamma parameter used for the seasonal component. If set to False, an non-seasonal model is fitted.
###

out1 <- HoltWinters(yy, beta = FALSE, gamma = TRUE)             # Holt-Winters Filtering -
